snippet.textDisplay:
To Zach: It appears that the dinner you made may have had a few common mistakes, obviously I'm not sure, but some important things to keep in mind...
1. Lots of common staple foods like rice, grains, potatoes offer great texture, but very little flavor so it's important even when mixing those things into a dish, that you flavor them individually to ensure maximum deliciousness.
2. If you're grilling broccoli, cut the crowns so that there's at least 1 flat side, that way you can guarantee a nicely charred side. Broccoli has a lot of water content so they can cook for awhile, and they'll even benefit a lot flavor wise if glazed in the frying pan.
3. It almost looked like the red onions you used were raw... but if you tried frying them, red onions don't have very good flavor or texture when fried. You'll want to switch to a sweet yellow onion (not just regular yellow onion) and let it fry until they're a nice caramelized brown. That's going to give you an excellent sweet and savory flavor.
4. As for lime juice, keep in mind that lime juice is excellent at cutting through other flavors giving your palate a nice fresh break, but in the absence of a strong sweet, savory, or spicy taste it can have a negative impact on your dish. Think like, having a salad without dressing and getting a bite that's mostly cilantro. It's an inappropriate use of the ingredient. haha
All that being said, keep up the effort and we look forward to your future cooking endeavors.
